  "texts": [
    "For example, in [37] it was shown that extreme opinions regarding a disease could trigger an increase in the spread of infection among individuals.",
    "Since the quantity Āω p +ε appears at the exponents of ( 22), the scenario corresponding to active agents can be very different compared to the one where inactive agents are involved.",
    "In fact, noticing that since |m Ā(t)| < ρ Ā(t) one has (ρ Ā(t) ± m Ā(t)) /ν p > 0 (here, the equalities hold if and only if all agents have opinions w = 1 or w = -1, which is the uninteresting case leading to the formation of Dirac delta distributions instead of the Beta distributions ( 22)), three possible situations must be distinguished:• ε ρ Ā(t)-m Ā(t) νp < (ω p + ε) ρ Ā(t)-m Ā(t) νp < 1 and/or ε ρ Ā(t)+m Ā(t) νp < (ω p + ε) ρ Ā(t)+m Ā(t) νp< 1, which corresponds to opinion polarization among both active and inactive agents;• 1 < ε ρ Ā(t)±m Ā(t) νp < (ω p + ε) ρ Ā(t)±m Ā(t) νp, which corresponds to consensus formation among both active and inactive agents;• ε ρ Ā(t)-m Ā(t) νp < 1 and/or ε ρ Ā(t)+m Ā(t) νp < 1, and 1 < (ω p + ε) ρ Ā(t)±m Ā(t) νp, which corresponds to opinion polarization among inactive agents and consensus formation among active agents.The third scenario is the most interesting one and highlights the importance of social interactions.",
    "Indeed, in this case, an effective compromise process among active agents prevents the formation of extreme opinion, while the absence of such process among inactive individuals leads to polarization.",
    "Moreover, there exists a unique threshold A * = A * (t) ∈ (-γ, γ), given byA * (t) = 1 ω p min ( ρ Ā(t) -m Ā(t) ν p, ρ Ā(t) + m Ā(t) ν p) -1 - ε ω p,which distinguishes between opinion polarization and consensus formation (this situation is illustrated in Figure 2)."
